Capuchins Movement Segmentation

Hidden Markov Models

AKDE Index Daily Travels

We applied Hidden Markov Models (HMMs; McClintock et al., 2020) to analyze the movement patterns of black capuchins in plantation landscapes and in INP. This approach allowed us to identify and compare discrete movement states between these contrasting landscapes and between contrasting environments within plantation landscapes (pine stands vs forest fragments). Within plantation landscapes we evaluated if movement states showed seasonal variation between native forest patches and pine stands associated to the seasonal bark-stripping behavior of capuchins (Mikich and Liebsch, 2014), expecting shorter steps and more convoluted movement patterns associated with this activity. The dataset consisted of GPS locations recorded at 30-minute intervals throughout the activity period (6:30 AM8:30 PM) for four groups in plantations and four groups in INP. Data spanned multiple years (2008, 2009, 2010, 2022, and 2023) covering the months of March to December, with June excluded due to inconsistent data collection. We classified movement, based on step length (distance between consecutive GPS locations) and turning angle (change in direction), into two behavioral states: Resident (short distances, sharp turns) and Transit (long distances, small turns). Step length represents movement magnitude (speed), while turning angle indicates directional persistence (Langrock et al., 2012). Resident behavior, linked to resting, social interactions, or slow foraging, had an initial mean step length of 20 m (SD = 20 m) and turning angle concentration (k) of 0.1. Transit behavior, associated with direct travel between resources, had a mean step length of 300 m (SD = 300 m) and k = 0.5. We employed the Viterbi algorithm to decode the most probable sequence of behavioral states for each individual (Joo et al., 2013). We evaluated model convergence by verifying stable parameter estimates across multiple runs with varying initial values, ensuring that the global maximum of the likelihood function was identified (McClintock and Michelot, 2018). These analyses were conducted using the R package momentuHMM (McClintock and Michelot, 2018).

2 Preparing data for HMM

There are some zeros, so I continue with the ZeroMass included.

I had to remove NAs, likely due to some issues when distances were calculated from the shape file. It was about 30 points, nothing serious. I also scaled both distances because many Warnings were triggered due to the unusual distribution of distances many zeros and some values of 1500 or more. I keep the columns with the variables in their original scale.

hmm_prep <- 
  prepData(
    hmm, type = "UTM",
    coordNames = c("x","y")) 
cutoff_date <- as.POSIXct("2022-07-21", tz = "UTC")  # Ajusta el ao segn corresponda

low <- hmm_prep %>% filter(t < cutoff_date)
high <- hmm_prep %>% filter(t >= cutoff_date)

3 Initial parameters

stepMean0_2 <- c(m1 = 20, m2 = 300)
stepSD0_2 <- c(sd1 = 20, sd2 = 300)
zeromass_2 <- c(zm1 = 0.05, zm2 =0.05) 
angleCon0_2 <- c(rho1  = 0.1, rho2 = 0.5)

stateNames_2 <- c("resident","transit")

dist_2 <- list(step = "gamma", angle = "wrpcauchy")
Par0_2 <- list(step=c(stepMean0_2, stepSD0_2), angle = c(angleCon0_2))

4 Model Fitting

4.1 Full year Models

Full-year models include data from March to December, that is low and high bark-stripping seasons. Sens stands for medium-aged pine stands

# Model 1: Null model
hmm2_null <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ 1)

# Model 2: Medium-aged distance
hmm2_sens <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_sensible)

# Model 4: Old distance
hmm2_old <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_old)

# Model 5: Young distance
hmm2_young <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_young)

# Model 6: Medium-aged + BN+SM distance
hmm2_sens_bnsm <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_sensible + dist_bnsm)

# Model 7: Medium-aged + Old distance
hmm2_old_sens <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_sensible + dist_old)

# Model 8: Medium-aged + Young distance
hmm2_young_sens <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_sensible + dist_young)

# Model 9: Full model
hmm2_full <-
  fitHMM(
    data = hmm_prep,
    nbStates = 2, dist = dist_2,
    Par0 = Par0_2, stateNames = stateNames_2,
    formula = ~ dist_sensible + dist_bnsm + dist_old + dist_young)

Failed fitting of the model including Distance to young and medium-aged stands, optimization algorithm nlm supplied a non-finite value. Model specification leads to numerical instability, possibly due to collinearity between covariates. Consequently, this model is not feasible to run as currently defined, and thus excluded.

aic_year <- AIC(hmm2_null, hmm2_sens, hmm2_bnsm, hmm2_old, hmm2_young, 
                hmm2_sens_bnsm, hmm2_old_sens, hmm2_full)

aic_year_df <- as.data.frame(aic_year) %>%
  mutate(Model = c("Forest Fragment", "Young", "Medium", "Null", 
                   "Old", "Old Pine + Medium", "Medium + Forest Fragment", "Full Model"),

  select(Model, AIC, deltaAIC)

aic_year_table <- flextable(aic_year_df) %>%

low <- as.data.frame(low) %>%

  group_by(tipouso_grouped) %>%

Figure 2. Distributions of step lengths and turning angles for two behavioral movement states of black capuchin monkeys in pine plantations of northeastern Argentina. The Resident state (blue) is characterized by short step lengths and more random turning angles, and was more common in native forest fragments (upper panels). The Transit state (red) is characterized by longer step lengths and more linear movements, and was more common in pine stands (lower panels).

HMM Iguazu National Park. Distributions of step lengths and turning angles for two behavioral movement states of black capuchin monkeys in Iguazu National Park, northeastern Argentina. The Resident state (blue) is characterized by short step lengths and more random turning angles. The Transit state (red) is characterized by longer step lengths and more linear movements.
